The '''Museum Collection Centre''' ('''MCC''') in [[Nechells]], [[Birmingham]], England is a 1.5 hectare building that holds 80% of [[Birmingham Museums Trust]]'s stored collections under one roof. It is one of the UK's largest museum stores.<ref name="heritageopendays">{{cite web|publisher=[[Heritage Open Days]]|title=Open Day at the Museum Collections Centre, Birmingham|url=http://www.heritageopendays.org.uk/directory/open-day-at-the-museum-collections-centre-birmingham|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140918063802/http://www.heritageopendays.org.uk/directory/open-day-at-the-museum-collections-centre-birmingham|dead-url=yes|archive-date=18 September 2014|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>
Among the thousands of objects stored there are [[steam engines]] (many of which are from the former [[Birmingham Museum of Science and Industry]]), sculptures, a collection of [[Austin Motor Company|Austin]], [[Rover (marque)|Rover]] and [[The MG Car Company Limited|MG]] motor cars, a [[red phone box]] and a [[Sinclair C5]].

It opens to the public monthly, or by arrangement. There are also other open days, which tend to take place during the Spring and Summer Bank Holidays.<ref name="MCCwhatson">{{cite web|publisher=[[Birmingham Museums Trust]]|title=Museum Collection Centre|url=http://www.birminghammuseums.org.uk/collection/museum-collection-centre|accessdate=28 May 2015}}</ref>

The Museum Collection Centre is also home to The Museum in a Box service which enables schools and community groups to borrow original artefacts.

In September 2014 then-trainee curator Lukas Large uncovered a taxidermied specimen of the long extinct North American [[passenger pigeon]] (''Ectopistes migratorius'') in the collection.<ref name="MCCPassengerPigeon">{{cite web|last1=Bentley|first1=David|title=Extinct bird rediscovered in Birmingham museum storage building|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/family-kids-news/extinct-bird-rediscovered-birmingham-museum-7738735|work=[[Birmingham Mail]]|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>

